\int f(\sqrt{c^2+x^2})x\, dx
f \in C
F'=f
F' \in C^1
c \in \mathbb{R}
G
F
u = \sqrt{c^2+x^2}
\begin{align} \int f(\sqrt{c^2+x^2})x\,dx &= \int\sqrt{c^2+x^2}\cdot f(\sqrt{c^2+x^2}) \frac{x}{\sqrt{c^2+x^2}}\,dx\\ &= \int u\cdot f(u)\,du\\ &= u\cdot F(u) - \int F(u)\,du\\ &= u\cdot F(u) - G(u)\\ &= \sqrt{c^2+x^2}\cdot F(\sqrt{c^2+x^2}) - G(\sqrt{c^2+x^2}). \end{align}
F(x)
f(\sqrt{x}).
t=x^2+c^2,  dt=2 x dx.
 \int f(\sqrt{x^2+c^2})x dx=\int f(\sqrt{t})  \frac 12 dt= \frac 12 F(t)= \frac{1}{2}F(\sqrt{x^2+c^2})+C. 
